lamic Political Thought -- tPart IV Religious Ideology and Political Control in Early Modern States -- t20 A New World Order -- t21 The State of the House of Osman (devlet-i al-i Osman) -- t22 The Safavids -- t23 India and the Mughals -- t24 The Decline and Reform of the Ottoman Empire -- tPart V Islam and the West -- t25 Modernism from the Ottoman Reforms to the Turkish Revolution -- t26 Conservatism and Modernism in Iran -- t27 Islamism -- t28 Islamism, Modernism and the Secular State -- tConclusion -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA complete history of Islamic political thought from early Islam (c.622–661) to the presentNow in its 2nd edition, this textbook describes and interprets all schools of Islamic political thought, their origins, inter-connections and meaning. It examines the Qur'an, the early Caliphate, classical Islamic philosophy and the political culture of the Ottoman and other empires. It covers major thinkers such as Averroes (Ibn Rushd) and Ibn Taymiyya as well as a number of lesser authors, and Ibn Khaldun is presented as one of the most original political theorists ever. It draws on a wide range of sources including writings on religion, law, philosophy and statecraft expressed in treatises, handbooks and political rhetoric.The new edition analyses the connections between religion and politics, covering the most recent developments in Islamic political thought and the most recent historical scholarship. It ends with a critical survey of reformism (or modernism) and Islamism (or fundamentalism) from the late-19th century up to the present day.Key FeaturesRevised and updated throughoutA new final section on Islam and the WestNew bibliographies of primary and secondary sourcesOnly book to cover the whole of Islamic political thought, past and present  aMode of access: Internet via World 